   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1836-09_page02.jpg"/><!--Letter begins on page two-->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>Edgeworth Town
                  <date when="1836-09-28"/>Sep<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1836</dateline>
             </opener>
            <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss Edgeworth</persName> presents her<lb/>
               compliments to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GrevX1">Mr Greville</persName><lb/>
               and returns him most <choice><orig>sin<lb/>
               cere</orig><reg>sincere</reg></choice> thanks for his very polite<lb/>
               note and his great forbearance<lb/>
               towards her. She is very much<lb/>
               ashamed and really shocked<lb/>
               that after all his goodness and<lb/>
               all the trouble he takes for her<lb/>
               such an annoyance, such<lb/>
               a most unreasonable <choice><orig>encroach<lb/>
               ment</orig><reg>encroachment</reg></choice> should have occurred -<lb/>
               - She has repeatedly warned her<lb/>
               correspondents, especially those<lb/>
               in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#US">America</placeName> that they must<lb/>
               not send any books under enclo<lb/>
               sure to the Council Office in <choice><orig>parti<lb/>
               cular</orig><reg>particular</reg></choice> - How this American lady<lb/>
               can have dared to sin against this<lb/>
               warning <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E</persName> cannot imagine<lb/>
               - only that it is impossible to drive<lb/>          
            </p>
            <p>
               <!--Where there's a page break record it inside the relevant body paragraph like this, 
                  with the self-closing page-break element. n="2" indicates the START of the second page.-->
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1836-09_page03.jpg"/>
               into American republican heads<lb/>
               anything relating to Aristocratic<lb/>
               English privileges - <choice><orig>Neverthe-<lb/>
               less</orig><reg>Nevertheless</reg></choice> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E</persName> will try again and<lb/>
               now absolutely prohibit this<lb/>
               offender from sending <hi rend="underline">any</hi><lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">thing</hi> to her friends the Clerks of<lb/>
               the Council -</p><lb/>
               <p>If it would not be too much<lb/>
               trouble <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1"><del>Miss E</del></persName> to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GrevX1">Mr. Greville</persName><lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E</persName> would beg the favor of<lb/>
               him to have the book in question<lb/>
               (which ought to be forfeited) sent<lb/>
               to N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>. 7 Somerset place-<lb/><!--This has no XML ID because could not identify if in England or Ireland-->
            </p>
            <closer>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p><!--A postscript goes here, outside the <closer>. --></p>
            </postscript>
            <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
            <!-- Format for postscripts. 
